				\begin{document}$$Z$$\end{document} and the J/ψ\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$J/\psi $$\end{document} resonances, requiring the presence of an isolated identified electron as the tag. Additional selection criteria are applied to obtain a high purity sample of electron candidates that can be used as probes to measure the reconstruction or identification efficiency. The measurements span different but overlapping kinematic regions and are studied as a function of the electron’s transverse momentum and pseudorapidity. The results are combined taking into account bin-to-bin correlations.

The ID provides precise reconstruction of tracks within |η|<2.5\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
