				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\eta $$\end{document}). These bins follow the detector geometry and the binning used for optimization and are as narrow as the size of the respective data set allows. Residual effects, due to the finite bin widths and kinematic differences of the physics processes used in the measurements, are expected to cancel in the data-to-MC efficiency ratio. Therefore, the combination of the different efficiency measurements is carried out using the data-to-MC ratios instead of the efficiencies themselves. The procedure for the combination is described in Sect. 7.3.

For the evaluation of the results of the measurements and their uncertainties using a given final state (Z→ee\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
