As in the other efficiency measurements, the backgrounds originate from hadronic jets as well as from photon conversions, Dalitz decays and semileptonic heavy-flavour hadron decays. The backgrounds for total and same-sign candidate events are estimated by extrapolating linearly the number of events from equally sized sidebands of the invariant-mass distributions above and below the Z mass peak to the signal region. As an estimate of the uncertainties, the measurement is performed by varying the invariant-mass window from 15 to 10 and 20 GeV\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\text {GeV}$$\end{document} around the Z\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$Z$$\end{document} mass, the width of the sidebands used in the background subtraction is changed to be 20, 25, or 30 GeV\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\text {GeV}$$\end{document}. All variations have very small effects on the measured rates. The average value of these variations is taken as the measured value, the RMS as the systematic uncertainty. The uncertainty returned by the minimization is accounted for as a statistical uncertainty.

